    lambda expressionlambda expression
    lambda expressionparsing of
    A lambda expression whose body is an expression is parsed as if the
    body consisted of a block containing a single return statement whose
    return expression is the body of the lambda expression.


\begin{eqnarray*}      
& \ll \texttt{(}\textit{name}_1\texttt{, }\ldots\texttt{, } \textit{name}_n \texttt{) =>}\ \textit{expression} \gg \\
& = \\
& \ll \texttt{(}\textit{name}_1\texttt{, }\ldots\texttt{, } \textit{name}_n \texttt{) => \{}\ \textbf{return} \ \textit{expression}\texttt{;}\ \texttt{\}} \gg
\end{eqnarray*}




\begin{eqnarray*}      
& \ll \texttt{(}\mathit{name}_1\texttt{, }\ldots\texttt{, } \mathit{name}_n \texttt{) =>}\ \mathit{expression} \gg \\
& = \\
& \ll \texttt{(}\mathit{name}_1\texttt{, }\ldots\texttt{, } \mathit{name}_n \texttt{) => \{}\ \textbf{\texttt{return}} \ \mathit{expression}\texttt{;}\ \texttt{\}} \gg
\end{eqnarray*}


	      A lambda expression whose body is a block is parsed as follows:



$\ll \texttt{(}\textit{name}_1\texttt{, }\ldots\texttt{, } \textit{name}_n \texttt{) =>}\ \textit{block} \gg\ \ =$




$\ll \texttt{(}\mathit{name}_1\texttt{, }\ldots\texttt{, } \mathit{name}_n \texttt{) =>}\ \mathit{block} \gg\ \ =$ \newline
\vspace{-8mm}




list("lambda_expression",
     list($\ll name_1 \gg$, $\ldots$, $\ll name_n \gg$),
     $\ll block \gg$)



